19:15.000 --> 19:35.000
Now let's turn to the research of scientists of the second half of the 20th century and the beginning of the 21st century, which were dedicated to how to design a work to be motivating.

19:35.000 --> 19:52.000
Perhaps the most famous model described is the Hackman model. Hackman argued that the main parameters of the task performed by the worker should be the following.

19:52.000 --> 20:13.000
1. The variety of skills that the worker should use, and, of course, have them in order to solve the tasks set before him. 2. The integrity of the task. What we have discussed is the planning stage, the performance stage, the control stage, and possible changes.

20:14.000 --> 20:24.000
3. The significance of the task. What is the significance of the task? A trivial semi-anecdote, a semi-example from the life of an army officer comes to mind.

20:24.000 --> 20:40.000
When in order to take on another private officer, the senior officer gives an order to sweep the square from here and until lunchtime. And when both of them understand that this task is almost pointless and is given precisely to take on a person.

20:40.000 --> 21:05.000
In some military organizations, I assure you, you will probably find such managers who have nothing to give to their subordinates on a certain day. Let's say, it's New Year's holidays or New Year's break when customers don't buy your company's services so actively, and the contract department sits on hungry loaves.

21:05.000 --> 21:21.000
Therefore, they can be given a task to sweep from here and until lunchtime. So, it is necessary to keep in mind how often we assign such reasonable tasks to our subordinates.

21:21.000 --> 21:38.000
The task should provide a certain autonomy for the employee. Very often, the function of control, the function of making changes, all this is delegated to the manager.

21:38.000 --> 22:02.000
On the other hand, your subordinate should, after all, for some time, solve the task autonomously enough, have the opportunity to request the resources he needs and perform the task without your interference, without the interference of the senior management in what he is doing.

22:02.000 --> 22:18.000
The fifth parameter, according to Hackman, is feedback. Based on his research, Hackman claims that if the task is such and satisfies all five conditions,

22:18.000 --> 22:38.000
then it creates certain positive psychological states for the employee, which allow him to perform the work more effectively, achieve a higher level of quality, be more satisfied and, accordingly, loyal to the employer,

22:38.000 --> 23:00.000
and show more zeal for work, including not being absent at work. Such absence in the West is called absenteeism, when a person sits on his chair, but in fact he is really absent somewhere.

23:00.000 --> 23:20.000
We believe that now, very often, with the help of the Internet, we can do this for a great benefit for both at home and to satisfy our needs in interacting with other people. Therefore, if we have the satisfaction of our work, we will most likely not do so.

23:20.000 --> 23:38.000
Accordingly, if our task satisfies all five criteria, we will consider that our work is well evaluated, that our work is significant, that this task is worth it.

23:38.000 --> 24:07.000
Of course, the Hackman model does not work in all cases. If you recall the theory of X and Y of Douglas McGregor, you will remember that, on the one hand, people can be lazy and not tuned in to intensive work, and, on the other hand, they are inspired by the very opportunity to work and create something.

24:07.000 --> 24:23.000
Therefore, we are all a little different, and even the same person in different periods of his life and career can rather relate to either the X generation or the Y generation.

24:23.000 --> 24:45.000
Therefore, this model, as Hackman claimed, will work only for those who are significantly in need of professional, social, and business growth. If this is not significant for the worker, then it will not work.

24:45.000 --> 25:10.000
Let's look at the factors that other researchers working in this field highlight. Lowler gives credit to the fact that feedback is important and very important in work. Hackman also had it, but Lowler emphasizes special attention to this aspect.

25:10.000 --> 25:20.000
The second factor is the degree of application of skills, not skills and knowledge, but skills that generalize the concept.

25:20.000 --> 25:43.000
The third factor is the independent control of choosing the path to achieve the goal. In this model, the leader does not set a specific task, but sets a goal for the worker, and the worker chooses the path to achieve the goal, and plans his work, controls it, and, of course, performs it.

25:43.000 --> 26:03.000
Robertson and Smith have the main criteria for how many tasks our subordinate solves, how complex these tasks are, and how involved our subordinates are in the activities of self-managed working teams.

26:03.000 --> 26:29.000
If we set a task for a group of people, for a team, and the whole team participates in the planning, implementation, control, and implementation of changes in the work, it turns out that each member of the team is more complete and has a more complete task in terms of its structure, which we talked about earlier.

26:30.000 --> 26:55.000
Again, Robertson and Smith say that the level of responsibility of the worker for choosing the path to achieve the goal is very important, and, of course, good relationships in the team in which he has to interact, and feedback from the person who set this goal, set this task.

26:56.000 --> 27:18.000
Turner and Lawrence emphasize the manager's attention at the end of the 20th century to the fact that work should be diverse, not monotonous, that a person should feel a certain independence that he needs to solve tasks.

27:19.000 --> 27:25.000
These scientists also said that the following are very important factors.

27:25.000 --> 27:39.000
These are the necessary interactions that are necessary for the solutions of tasks before the worker, for example, the interaction of the manager and subordinates, and additional interactions that are necessary for our worker to solve these tasks.

27:40.000 --> 27:51.000
For example, interaction with the workers of other companies, possibly with clients who are outside the company. This is also very important.

27:52.000 --> 28:10.000
Cooper emphasized the attention of the modern manager on the features set before our subordinates. The goal itself should motivate a person to do his job effectively.

28:10.000 --> 28:36.000
From the point of view of philosophy or ideology, what do we, as managers, achieve when designing the work of a certain person? In fact, everything is very simple. We achieve a balance between organizational goals and goals of our specific worker, Ivan Ivanovich, who works in our team today.

