Let's now turn to another model that was also developed in the last century, but now, at the beginning of the 21st century, has undergone some changes and can be used for your benefit.

48:25.000 --> 48:41.000
What is this model? It is a model of an organization as a socio-technical system. Again, starting from the industrialization era, it was revealed that many technical innovations do not lead to the expected results.

48:41.000 --> 48:54.000
Why? Because when designing them, certain requirements were not taken into account, which the social subsystem of the organization sets out for how such innovations should be introduced.

48:55.000 --> 49:04.000
In the 20th century, a number of scientists proposed the following model. Our organization consists of two main systems.

49:04.000 --> 49:16.000
This is the technical subsystem, these are the mechanisms, equipment, software, technological solutions of a variety of nature, and the social system.

49:17.000 --> 49:26.000
These are the people working in the organization, this is the relationship between them, this is the knowledge, skills, competencies, needs of our worker.

49:27.000 --> 49:32.000
This is the system of rewards and the structure of power and management in the organization.

49:33.000 --> 49:44.000
The basic principles of socio-technical design were developed in the 1970s, but then, at the beginning of the 21st century, were somewhat improved.

49:44.000 --> 49:56.000
What are they talking about? That the design of the workplace in the situation of today's constant changes should be done as follows.

49:56.000 --> 50:16.000
First, the design process must correspond to its goals. It's very simple. If you design the place of Ivan Ivanovich, you should involve him in the design process, in planning what he will do tomorrow, the day after tomorrow, and not to make it out of what he did the day before yesterday.

50:16.000 --> 50:34.000
The second principle is that the goals of the design must be clear, clear, and clearly set, but the tools and ways to achieve the goals can be chosen by the worker or a group of workers independently.

50:34.000 --> 50:58.000
For example, one of the Western organizations implemented the following program. All the premises of the organization were given to the workers to organize the workplace themselves in the way they were comfortable with the tasks assigned to them.

50:58.000 --> 51:16.000
The third principle is that the function of controlling possible deviations should be implemented as closely as possible to the place of potential deviation.

51:16.000 --> 51:34.000
If we turn to the traditional hierarchical structure of the organization, for example, the function of control is implemented in the service of internal control or management of the organization, and defects and defects may appear in the production process.

51:34.000 --> 51:59.000
If the worker at the production site is not motivated to declare a defect, he can declare a defect, a low-quality material, at the output of the production process, only by the IT department. Accordingly, through the IT manager, through the division manager, this signal will return back to the worker who made a mistake.

51:59.000 --> 52:24.000
Thus, the processing time of this alarm signal about a defect is increasingly increased, and in the process of working with a defective product, several dozen people are already busy. Accordingly, the work with a defective product is becoming more expensive.

52:25.000 --> 52:40.000
I can give an example of one of the Russian enterprises that acted as follows. This is a company that produces GoFrotars, called Gotek.

52:40.000 --> 52:53.000
The employees of the production process were motivated to declare defective products if they fall at any stage of the production cycle to this worker.

52:53.000 --> 53:14.000
At the same time, he received bonuses not only for a certain production, but also made so many boxes. And the number of boxes paid included the defective products or blanks that reached him at this stage.

53:14.000 --> 53:23.000
Thus, the company increased the quality of the produced product and reduced the percentage of the final defect.

53:24.000 --> 53:34.000
The next principle of socio-technical design is that managers are multifunctional people by nature.

53:34.000 --> 53:54.000
Do not give your subordinate a task such as screwing a nut and that's it. Consider your subordinate as a tool, although I don't like this word, which can perform various functions and tasks, and give them to him.

53:55.000 --> 54:09.000
The next principle is the principle of open borders. In an organization, you can not always design a job, taking into account only the tasks that are before the subordinate.

54:09.000 --> 54:22.000
And not only can you take into account such tasks, but you should take into account and keep in mind the tasks that go beyond the team that is subordinate to him.

54:22.000 --> 54:32.000
This will motivate the subordinates to expand the circle of vision and to build an effective system of interaction with colleagues of other departments.

54:32.000 --> 54:44.000
The next principle of socio-technical design says that all subordinates should receive the information they need for work and when it is necessary.

54:44.000 --> 54:48.000
It makes no sense to comment here.

