The next principle says that all support systems of socio-technical design are a system of rewards, a system of training a set of employees.

55:03.000 --> 55:15.000
And many other organizational subsystems should be congruent with the goals and tasks of socio-technical design, and not contradict them.

55:15.000 --> 55:28.000
For example, we try to introduce collective working principles into the organization, but the system of rewards is focused exclusively on individual rewards.

55:28.000 --> 55:42.000
Thus, the work of our self-managed teams will not be supported by this system, they will be in contradiction and will not give the expected result.

55:42.000 --> 55:56.000
The next principle is also very simple. The manager should take into account the common human values, personal autonomy, the right to freedom of speech, and so on.

55:56.000 --> 56:02.000
The last principle of socio-technical design is the principle of imperfection.

56:02.000 --> 56:10.000
We have designed work for our subordinates, and, as it seems to us, today, in the most optimal and effective way.

56:10.000 --> 56:24.000
But we cannot stop here, because tomorrow the preferences of our employees will change, and specialization will require some change of skills, knowledge, and so on.

56:24.000 --> 56:31.000
Therefore, this is a continuous process, a cyclical process that must be carried out in the organization permanently.

56:31.000 --> 56:48.000
Today's work on socio-technical design is very often focused on how various automation and software means are being introduced into our companies,

56:48.000 --> 56:58.000
which, among other things, aims to improve certain social functions of the organization, and helps us to interact in a different way.

56:58.000 --> 57:10.000
